      <h2 id="problem">The problem with white PDFs</h2>
      <p>Every colour in a white-background PDF flips to its opposite when you invert it — white becomes black, black becomes white, dark navy turns bright yellow. It is essentially toggling dark mode for any PDF file, regardless of how it was created or which application originally generated it.</p>
      <p>Most people discover they need this at the worst possible moment: reviewing lecture notes at 2 AM, reading a scanned contract on a max-brightness laptop, or preparing a design presentation where the dark colour scheme just demands a dark document to match. The solution should take seconds. It usually takes much longer — or costs money. That's the gap ihatepdf.cv was built to close.</p>

      <div class="blog-rule"></div>

      <h2 id="why-invert">Why invert PDF colours at all?</h2>
      <p>There are more reasons than you might expect.</p>

      <div class="opt-card">
        <span class="opt-num">01</span>
        <div>
          <div class="opt-title">Night reading and eye comfort</div>
          <div class="opt-body">A white-background PDF at full screen brightness is roughly equivalent to staring into a desk lamp. An inverted PDF — dark background, light text — is dramatically easier to read in low-light environments and causes significantly less eye fatigue during long reading sessions.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="opt-card">
        <span class="opt-num">02</span>
        <div>
          <div class="opt-title">Accessibility and visual sensitivity</div>
          <div class="opt-body">For people with light sensitivity, photophobia, migraines, or certain visual impairments, high-contrast dark documents are not a preference — they are a necessity. Many PDF readers offer a dark mode, but it only simulates inversion at the display level. An actually inverted file works correctly everywhere: in email previews, browser viewers, and older PDF readers that have no dark mode at all.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="opt-card">
        <span class="opt-num">03</span>
        <div>
          <div class="opt-title">Ink and toner savings when printing</div>
          <div class="opt-body">A heavily white document consumes far more ink to print than its dark-background equivalent. Inverting before printing is a legitimate toner-saving strategy for draft documents, internal reports, and worksheets where appearance is secondary to readability.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="opt-card">
        <span class="opt-num">04</span>
        <div>
          <div class="opt-title">Design and presentation contexts</div>
          <div class="opt-body">Architects, UX designers, and anyone presenting on a dark-themed slide deck sometimes needs supporting documents that match the visual context. A white PDF dropped into a dark presentation looks jarring. An inverted one looks intentional.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

