      <h2 id="tips">Tips for the best results</h2>
      <p>A few things worth knowing before you invert.</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Text-only documents invert perfectly.</strong> A contract, essay, or report with no embedded images will come back with clean white text on a black background. Every character stays crisp.</li>
        <li><strong>Photos invert to their colour opposite.</strong> Full-colour photographs embedded in a PDF will invert along with everything else. A sunset photo becomes a striking cyan-and-blue negative. For most documents this is irrelevant; for design-heavy PDFs it is worth previewing first.</li>
        <li><strong>Scanned PDFs are raster images.</strong> A PDF that is a scanned page — not a text-layer PDF — is essentially a photograph. It inverts cleanly to a dark background with light text, which is usually exactly what you want.</li>
        <li><strong>The original is untouched.</strong> The tool returns a new file. Your uploaded original is never modified. Keep both if you need the standard version for printing or sharing.</li>
        <li><strong>Pair with Compress PDF if needed.</strong> After inverting, if your file size has grown, run it through the <a href="https://www.ihatepdf.cv/compress-pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Compress PDF</a> tool on ihatepdf.cv to bring it back down — same zero-friction experience.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="callout"><strong>One last thing:</strong> if your PDF has a dark header or cover page that looks correct in the original, remember that it will become light after inversion. It is worth scrolling through the output for two seconds before closing the tab, just to confirm the result is what you expected.</div>

